From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Codex <codex@openai.com>
Date: Thu, 18 Jun 2026 16:20:00 +0700
Subject: [PATCH] net/sched: cls_flower: reject tcp_flags without ip_proto tcp

`tc flower` can currently accept a rule like:

  protocol ip flower tcp_flags 0x02/0x02 action drop

The classifier only copies `TCA_FLOWER_KEY_TCP_FLAGS` into the flow key when
`ip_proto` resolves to TCP, but it does not reject the malformed combination
when TCP was not selected. The result is a silently broadened IPv4 drop rule,
which is especially dangerous on hardware-offloaded paths because the rule can
still install in hardware with the TCP flags match lost.

Reject the malformed rule early with a clear extack so userspace and hardware
drivers both see an explicit failure instead of a widened match.

Signed-off-by: Codex <codex@openai.com>
---
 net/sched/cls_flower.c | 10 ++++++++++
 1 file changed, 10 insertions(+)

--- a/net/sched/cls_flower.c
+++ b/net/sched/cls_flower.c
@@ -1927,6 +1927,16 @@
 		fl_set_key_val(tb, &key->basic.ip_proto, TCA_FLOWER_KEY_IP_PROTO,
 			       &mask->basic.ip_proto, TCA_FLOWER_UNSPEC,
 			       sizeof(key->basic.ip_proto));
+
+		if ((tb[TCA_FLOWER_KEY_TCP_FLAGS] ||
+		     tb[TCA_FLOWER_KEY_TCP_FLAGS_MASK]) &&
+		    key->basic.ip_proto != IPPROTO_TCP) {
+			NL_SET_ERR_MSG_ATTR(extack,
+					    tb[TCA_FLOWER_KEY_TCP_FLAGS] ?: tb[TCA_FLOWER_KEY_TCP_FLAGS_MASK],
+					    "tcp_flags match requires ip_proto tcp");
+			return -EINVAL;
+		}
+
 		fl_set_key_ip(tb, false, &key->ip, &mask->ip);
 	}
 
